The Current Financial Thing
Men, it has been well said, think in herds; it will be seen that they go ma=
d in herds, while they only recover their senses slowly, and one by one.
It=E2=80=99s funny that those who take finance particularly seriously dismi=
ss meme stocks.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CLeave the memes to the kids,=E2=80=9D they chortle during long bul=
l runs, =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll get back to doing real finance once the bubb=
le bursts and the madness subsides.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
And then the markets turn and rates go up and a war starts and crypto tanks=
 and growth stocks tank and meme stocks really tank and startups will, inev=
itably, once they=E2=80=99re forced to raise and mark-to-market, tank.=C2=
=A0
=E2=80=9CBe careful out there, there's gonna be a lot more pain. Rates will=
 continue to rise and multiples will continue to compress and companies wil=
l need to tighten their belts and growth will slow and senior leadership wi=
ll leave and growth will slow further and all but a few of the best startup=
s =E2=80=93 let alone crypto projects =E2=80=93 will die.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Which is funny because this, too, is a meme. It=E2=80=99s a story that peop=
le tell each other to cut through all of the trillions of things they could=
 be paying attention to. Re-telling this story is a way for people to signa=
l that they, too, get it. That they, too, take finance seriously. That they=
, too, are looking forward to the separation of wheat and chaff.=C2=A0
The difference is, meme stock traders know they=E2=80=99re trading a meme.
Now certainly, the growth bears have some math on their side. The higher th=
e discount rate, the lower the present value. But that=E2=80=99s easy. That=
=E2=80=99s the same first-order thinking that everyone=E2=80=99s agreed upo=
n. The idea that printing has led to inflation which will lead to more hike=
s which will kill growth companies and risk assets is The Current Financial=
 Thing.=C2=A0
So everyone talks about rising rates and hyperinflation and war and food sh=
ortages and nuclear threats and supply chain issues and energy prices and I=
PO windows slammed shut. They create =E2=80=93 and may often feel =E2=80=93=
 fear, uncertainty, and doubt (FUD).
The markets are too complex for anyone to know, with the degree of confiden=
ce with which some people pretend to know, what=E2=80=99s going to happen t=
omorrow, let alone in a week, a month, or a year. That=E2=80=99s what memes=
 are for. That=E2=80=99s why people agree on The Current Financial Thing. T=
hrow in Twitter=E2=80=99s algorithmic feed, and people can come to agree wi=
th each other more strongly, more quickly than ever before.=C2=A0
